('chunk_e40686528282d481c0','file_a8bb6ddf9d5c59f486','biology.md','Concept: Carbohydrates','**Definition.** Carbohydrates are biomolecules made of C, H and O (usually H:O in a 2:1 ratio). They are classified as **monosaccharides** (single sugars, e.g. glucose, fructose), **disaccharides** (two sugars, e.g. sucrose, maltose), and **polysaccharides** (many sugars, e.g. starch, glycogen, cellulose).

**Functions:** immediate **energy source** (glucose), **energy storage** (starch in plants, glycogen in animals), and **structural** support (cellulose in plant cell walls).

**Real-world example.** Rice and potatoes store starch; the cellulose in vegetables provides dietary fibre.

**Analogy.** A monosaccharide is a single train carriage; a polysaccharide is a long train of many carriages linked together.

**Why it matters.** Carbohydrates fuel almost every cell, especially the brain and muscles during activity.

**Verbal diagram.** Picture glucose as a six-carbon ring. Two rings joined = a disaccharide (with water removed). Hundreds of rings branched or coiled = starch/glycogen.

**Misconception.** *"All sugars are the same."* Wrong — simple sugars are absorbed quickly (rapid energy spike), while complex polysaccharides release energy slowly, giving steadier fuel.

**Command-term questions**
- *(Recall)* **State** the three classes of carbohydrate with one example each.
- *(Apply)* **Outline** why an athlete eats pasta ("carb-loading") before a marathon.
- *(Analyse/Evaluate)* **Compare** the roles of starch and cellulose in a plant.

---','{"concept":1,"carbohydrates":3,"definition":1,"are":4,"biomolecules":1,"made":1,"and":6,"usually":1,"ratio":1,"they":1,"classified":1,"monosaccharides":1,"single":2,"sugars":5,"glucose":3,"fructose":1,"disaccharides":1,"two":2,"sucrose":1,"maltose":1,"polysaccharides":2,"many":2,"starch":5,"glycogen":3,"cellulose":4,"functions":1,"immediate":1,"energy":4,"source":1,"storage":1,"plants":1,"animals":1,"structural":1,"support":1,"plant":2,"cell":2,"walls":1,"real":1,"world":1,"example":2,"rice":1,"potatoes":1,"store":1,"the":5,"vegetables":1,"provides":1,"dietary":1,"fibre":1,"analogy":1,"monosaccharide":1,"train":2,"carriage":1,"polysaccharide":1,"long":1,"carriages":1,"linked":1,"together":1,"why":2,"matters":1,"fuel":2,"almost":1,"every":1,"especially":1,"brain":1,"muscles":1,"during":1,"activity":1,"verbal":1,"diagram":1,"picture":1,"six":1,"carbon":1,"ring":1,"rings":2,"joined":1,"disaccharide":1,"with":2,"water":1,"removed":1,"hundreds":1,"branched":1,"coiled":1,"misconception":1,"all":1,"same":1,"wrong":1,"simple":1,"absorbed":1,"quickly":1,"rapid":1,"spike":1,"while":1,"complex":1,"release":1,"slowly":1,"giving":1,"steadier":1,"command":1,"term":1,"questions":1,"recall":1,"state":1,"three":1,"classes":1,"carbohydrate":1,"one":1,"each":1,"apply":1,"outline":1,"athlete":1,"eats":1,"pasta":1,"carb":1,"loading":1,"before":1,"marathon":1,"analyse":1,"evaluate":1,"compare":1,"roles":1}'::jsonb),
('chunk_f456e2d348148c984d','file_a8bb6ddf9d5c59f486','biology.md','Concept: Proteins','**Definition.** Proteins are polymers of **amino acids** containing C, H, O and **N** (nitrogen). Around 20 different amino acids combine in chains that fold into specific 3-D shapes.

**Functions:** **enzymes** (biological catalysts), **structural** (collagen, keratin, muscle), **transport** (haemoglobin carries oxygen), and **hormones** (e.g. insulin).

**Real-world example.** Egg white, meat, beans and lentils are protein-rich; muscle growth after exercise needs dietary protein.

**Analogy.** Amino acids are letters; a protein is a word whose meaning (function) depends on the exact sequence and folding.

**Why it matters.** Proteins do most of the "work" in cells; without dietary protein the body cannot grow or repair.

**Misconception.** *"More protein always builds more muscle."* Wrong — muscle growth needs training plus adequate (not excessive) protein; surplus is broken down or stored as fat.

**Command-term questions**
- *(Recall)* **State** the four elements found in all proteins.
- *(Apply)* **Identify** the protein function represented by haemoglobin.
- *(Analyse/Evaluate)* **Explain** how a change in amino acid sequence could stop a protein working.

---','{"concept":1,"proteins":4,"definition":1,"are":3,"polymers":1,"amino":4,"acids":3,"containing":1,"and":4,"nitrogen":1,"around":1,"different":1,"combine":1,"chains":1,"that":1,"fold":1,"into":1,"specific":1,"shapes":1,"functions":1,"enzymes":1,"biological":1,"catalysts":1,"structural":1,"collagen":1,"keratin":1,"muscle":4,"transport":1,"haemoglobin":2,"carries":1,"oxygen":1,"hormones":1,"insulin":1,"real":1,"world":1,"example":1,"egg":1,"white":1,"meat":1,"beans":1,"lentils":1,"protein":8,"rich":1,"growth":2,"after":1,"exercise":1,"needs":2,"dietary":2,"analogy":1,"letters":1,"word":1,"whose":1,"meaning":1,"function":2,"depends":1,"the":5,"exact":1,"sequence":2,"folding":1,"why":1,"matters":1,"most":1,"work":1,"cells":1,"without":1,"body":1,"cannot":1,"grow":1,"repair":1,"misconception":1,"more":2,"always":1,"builds":1,"wrong":1,"training":1,"plus":1,"adequate":1,"not":1,"excessive":1,"surplus":1,"broken":1,"down":1,"stored":1,"fat":1,"command":1,"term":1,"questions":1,"recall":1,"state":1,"four":1,"elements":1,"found":1,"all":1,"apply":1,"identify":1,"represented":1,"analyse":1,"evaluate":1,"explain":1,"how":1,"change":1,"acid":1,"could":1,"stop":1,"working":1}'::jsonb),
('chunk_d7d0045a1414815523','file_a8bb6ddf9d5c59f486','biology.md','Concept: Lipids (fats and oils)','**Definition.** Lipids are biomolecules made of C, H and O, built from **fatty acids and glycerol**. A **triglyceride** is one glycerol joined to three fatty acids.

**Functions:** long-term **energy storage** (more energy per gram than carbohydrate), **membranes** (phospholipids form cell membranes), **insulation** and protection of organs.

**Real-world example.** Butter and oils are lipids; blubber insulates whales; the fat layer under skin keeps humans warm.

**Analogy.** A triglyceride is like a capital "E" — the spine is glycerol and the three arms are fatty acid tails.

**Why it matters.** Lipids store energy compactly, cushion organs, and every cell is wrapped in a lipid membrane.

**Misconception.** *"All fats are bad for you."* Wrong — unsaturated fats (nuts, fish, olive oil) are essential; the concern is excess saturated and trans fats.

**Command-term questions**
- *(Recall)* **State** the building blocks of a lipid.
- *(Apply)* **Outline** two reasons a seal has a thick fat layer.
- *(Analyse/Evaluate)* **Discuss** why lipids store more energy per gram than carbohydrates.

---','{"concept":1,"lipids":5,"fats":4,"and":8,"oils":2,"definition":1,"are":5,"biomolecules":1,"made":1,"built":1,"from":1,"fatty":3,"acids":2,"glycerol":3,"triglyceride":2,"one":1,"joined":1,"three":2,"functions":1,"long":1,"term":2,"energy":4,"storage":1,"more":2,"per":2,"gram":2,"than":2,"carbohydrate":1,"membranes":2,"phospholipids":1,"form":1,"cell":2,"insulation":1,"protection":1,"organs":2,"real":1,"world":1,"example":1,"butter":1,"blubber":1,"insulates":1,"whales":1,"the":5,"fat":2,"layer":2,"under":1,"skin":1,"keeps":1,"humans":1,"warm":1,"analogy":1,"like":1,"capital":1,"spine":1,"arms":1,"acid":1,"tails":1,"why":2,"matters":1,"store":2,"compactly":1,"cushion":1,"every":1,"wrapped":1,"lipid":2,"membrane":1,"misconception":1,"all":1,"bad":1,"for":1,"you":1,"wrong":1,"unsaturated":1,"nuts":1,"fish":1,"olive":1,"oil":1,"essential":1,"concern":1,"excess":1,"saturated":1,"trans":1,"command":1,"questions":1,"recall":1,"state":1,"building":1,"blocks":1,"apply":1,"outline":1,"two":1,"reasons":1,"seal":1,"has":1,"thick":1,"analyse":1,"evaluate":1,"discuss":1,"carbohydrates":1}'::jsonb),
('chunk_096a632b57530693b8','file_a8bb6ddf9d5c59f486','biology.md','Concept: Nucleic acids','**Definition.** Nucleic acids (DNA and RNA) are polymers of **nucleotides** and contain C, H, O, N and **P** (phosphorus). Each nucleotide has a sugar, a phosphate group and a nitrogenous base.

**Function:** store and carry **genetic information** — the instructions to build proteins and to pass traits to offspring.

**Real-world example.** DNA in every cell nucleus determines eye colour and other inherited features.

**Analogy.** DNA is a twisted ladder (double helix); the rungs are pairs of bases spelling a coded instruction manual.

**Why it matters.** Nucleic acids are the information system that makes each organism unique and directs all cell activity.

**Verbal diagram.** Imagine two long strands twisting around each other (double helix). Between them, paired bases (A–T, C–G) form the rungs; a sugar-phosphate backbone forms the rails.

**Misconception.** *"DNA is only found in humans / only in the nucleus."* Wrong — all living cells contain DNA, and small amounts also sit in mitochondria (and chloroplasts in plants).

**Command-term questions**
- *(Recall)* **State** the monomer of a nucleic acid and name the two types of nucleic acid.
- *(Apply)* **Identify** which element distinguishes nucleic acids from carbohydrates.
- *(Analyse/Evaluate)* **Explain** why nucleic acids are described as "information molecules."

---','{"concept":1,"nucleic":7,"acids":5,"definition":1,"dna":5,"and":11,"rna":1,"are":4,"polymers":1,"nucleotides":1,"contain":2,"phosphorus":1,"each":3,"nucleotide":1,"has":1,"sugar":2,"phosphate":2,"group":1,"nitrogenous":1,"base":1,"function":1,"store":1,"carry":1,"genetic":1,"information":3,"the":8,"instructions":1,"build":1,"proteins":1,"pass":1,"traits":1,"offspring":1,"real":1,"world":1,"example":1,"every":1,"cell":2,"nucleus":2,"determines":1,"eye":1,"colour":1,"other":2,"inherited":1,"features":1,"analogy":1,"twisted":1,"ladder":1,"double":2,"helix":2,"rungs":2,"pairs":1,"bases":2,"spelling":1,"coded":1,"instruction":1,"manual":1,"why":2,"matters":1,"system":1,"that":1,"makes":1,"organism":1,"unique":1,"directs":1,"all":2,"activity":1,"verbal":1,"diagram":1,"imagine":1,"two":2,"long":1,"strands":1,"twisting":1,"around":1,"between":1,"them":1,"paired":1,"form":1,"backbone":1,"forms":1,"rails":1,"misconception":1,"only":2,"found":1,"humans":1,"wrong":1,"living":1,"cells":1,"small":1,"amounts":1,"also":1,"sit":1,"mitochondria":1,"chloroplasts":1,"plants":1,"command":1,"term":1,"questions":1,"recall":1,"state":1,"monomer":1,"acid":2,"name":1,"types":1,"apply":1,"identify":1,"which":1,"element":1,"distinguishes":1,"from":1,"carbohydrates":1,"analyse":1,"evaluate":1,"explain":1,"described":1,"molecules":1}'::jsonb),
('chunk_69cedfe91f3b00c93c','file_a8bb6ddf9d5c59f486','biology.md','Concept: Macronutrients vs. micronutrients & deficiency diseases','**Definition.** **Macronutrients** are nutrients needed in large amounts — **carbohydrates, proteins, fats** (plus water and fibre). **Micronutrients** are needed in tiny amounts — **vitamins and minerals**. A shortage of a nutrient causes a **deficiency disease**.

| Micronutrient | Main role | Deficiency effect |
|---------------|-----------|-------------------|
| Vitamin A | Vision, immune health | Night blindness |
| Vitamin C | Skin, healing, immunity | Scurvy (bleeding gums) |
| Vitamin D | Calcium absorption, bones | Rickets (soft/bent bones) |
| Calcium (mineral) | Bones, teeth, nerves | Weak bones, osteoporosis |
| Iron (mineral) | Haemoglobin in red blood cells | Anaemia (tiredness, pale) |

**Real-world example.** Sailors on long voyages without fresh fruit developed scurvy from lack of vitamin C.

**Analogy.** Macronutrients are the bricks and fuel of a building; micronutrients are the small screws and wiring — tiny, but the building fails without them.

**Why it matters.** Even a well-fed person can be ill if missing a single vitamin or mineral.

**Misconception.** *"If I eat enough food I can''t be malnourished."* Wrong — you can eat plenty of calories yet lack specific micronutrients ("hidden hunger").

**Command-term questions**
- *(Recall)* **List** two vitamins and two minerals with one function each.
- *(Apply)* **Identify** the likely deficiency in a child with soft, bowed leg bones.
- *(Analyse/Evaluate)* **Explain** why vitamin D and calcium deficiencies produce similar bone problems.

---','{"concept":1,"macronutrients":3,"micronutrients":4,"deficiency":4,"diseases":1,"definition":1,"are":4,"nutrients":1,"needed":2,"large":1,"amounts":2,"carbohydrates":1,"proteins":1,"fats":1,"plus":1,"water":1,"and":6,"fibre":1,"tiny":2,"vitamins":2,"minerals":2,"shortage":1,"nutrient":1,"causes":1,"disease":1,"micronutrient":1,"main":1,"role":1,"effect":1,"vitamin":6,"vision":1,"immune":1,"health":1,"night":1,"blindness":1,"skin":1,"healing":1,"immunity":1,"scurvy":2,"bleeding":1,"gums":1,"calcium":3,"absorption":1,"bones":5,"rickets":1,"soft":2,"bent":1,"mineral":3,"teeth":1,"nerves":1,"weak":1,"osteoporosis":1,"iron":1,"haemoglobin":1,"red":1,"blood":1,"cells":1,"anaemia":1,"tiredness":1,"pale":1,"real":1,"world":1,"example":1,"sailors":1,"long":1,"voyages":1,"without":2,"fresh":1,"fruit":1,"developed":1,"from":1,"lack":2,"analogy":1,"the":4,"bricks":1,"fuel":1,"building":2,"small":1,"screws":1,"wiring":1,"but":1,"fails":1,"them":1,"why":2,"matters":1,"even":1,"well":1,"fed":1,"person":1,"can":3,"ill":1,"missing":1,"single":1,"misconception":1,"eat":2,"enough":1,"food":1,"malnourished":1,"wrong":1,"you":1,"plenty":1,"calories":1,"yet":1,"specific":1,"hidden":1,"hunger":1,"command":1,"term":1,"questions":1,"recall":1,"list":1,"two":2,"with":2,"one":1,"function":1,"each":1,"apply":1,"identify":1,"likely":1,"child":1,"bowed":1,"leg":1,"analyse":1,"evaluate":1,"explain":1,"deficiencies":1,"produce":1,"similar":1,"bone":1,"problems":1}'::jsonb),
('chunk_76f78343ef2912d797','file_a8bb6ddf9d5c59f486','biology.md','Concept: A balanced diet, food groups and dietary requirements','**Definition.** A **balanced diet** provides all nutrients in the correct proportions and amounts to meet the body''s needs. It is usually shown as a **food pyramid** or **food plate** dividing food into groups (grains, fruits, vegetables, protein foods, dairy, and small amounts of fats/sugars).

**Requirements vary by:**
- **Age:** infants need lots of energy and protein for growth; teenagers need calcium for bones; the elderly need fewer calories but adequate protein and calcium.
- **Gender:** menstruating females need more **iron** to replace blood loss.
- **Activity level:** athletes and manual workers need more energy (calories).
- **Basal Metabolic Rate (BMR):** the energy the body uses at complete rest just to stay alive (breathing, heartbeat, temperature). A higher BMR means higher baseline calorie needs.

**Real-world example.** A pregnant woman needs extra iron, calcium and folate; an office worker needs fewer calories than a construction worker of the same size.

**Analogy.** A balanced diet is like a balanced budget — spend (calories in) roughly matched to needs (calories out), with the right mix of "currencies" (nutrients).

**Why it matters.** Matching intake to individual needs prevents both deficiency and obesity.

**Misconception.** *"Everyone needs the same diet."* Wrong — needs change with age, sex, size and activity; a plan good for an athlete may overfeed a sedentary person.

**Command-term questions**
- *(Recall)* **Define** basal metabolic rate.
- *(Apply)* **Outline** why a menstruating teenage girl needs more iron than a boy of the same age.
- *(Analyse/Evaluate)* **Discuss** how activity level and BMR together determine daily calorie needs.

---','{"concept":1,"balanced":4,"diet":4,"food":4,"groups":2,"and":10,"dietary":1,"requirements":2,"definition":1,"provides":1,"all":1,"nutrients":2,"the":9,"correct":1,"proportions":1,"amounts":2,"meet":1,"body":2,"needs":10,"usually":1,"shown":1,"pyramid":1,"plate":1,"dividing":1,"into":1,"grains":1,"fruits":1,"vegetables":1,"protein":3,"foods":1,"dairy":1,"small":1,"fats":1,"sugars":1,"vary":1,"age":3,"infants":1,"need":5,"lots":1,"energy":3,"for":3,"growth":1,"teenagers":1,"calcium":3,"bones":1,"elderly":1,"fewer":2,"calories":5,"but":1,"adequate":1,"gender":1,"menstruating":2,"females":1,"more":3,"iron":3,"replace":1,"blood":1,"loss":1,"activity":3,"level":2,"athletes":1,"manual":1,"workers":1,"basal":2,"metabolic":2,"rate":2,"bmr":3,"uses":1,"complete":1,"rest":1,"just":1,"stay":1,"alive":1,"breathing":1,"heartbeat":1,"temperature":1,"higher":2,"means":1,"baseline":1,"calorie":2,"real":1,"world":1,"example":1,"pregnant":1,"woman":1,"extra":1,"folate":1,"office":1,"worker":2,"than":2,"construction":1,"same":3,"size":2,"analogy":1,"like":1,"budget":1,"spend":1,"roughly":1,"matched":1,"out":1,"with":2,"right":1,"mix":1,"currencies":1,"why":2,"matters":1,"matching":1,"intake":1,"individual":1,"prevents":1,"both":1,"deficiency":1,"obesity":1,"misconception":1,"everyone":1,"wrong":1,"change":1,"sex":1,"plan":1,"good":1,"athlete":1,"may":1,"overfeed":1,"sedentary":1,"person":1,"command":1,"term":1,"questions":1,"recall":1,"define":1,"apply":1,"outline":1,"teenage":1,"girl":1,"boy":1,"analyse":1,"evaluate":1,"discuss":1,"how":1,"together":1,"determine":1,"daily":1}'::jsonb);